518599629402, -0.03481680154800415, 0.0750536322593689, -0.014445757493376732, 0.0064879595302045345, 0.03996123746037483, 0.011029531247913837, 0.0003550794208422303, -0.02250690385699272, -0.03523019328713417, 0.004179853480309248, -0.028753718361258507, 0.01125345192849636, -0.007085081655532122, -0.00148562784306705, -0.0007786986534483731, -0.015938563272356987, 0.0074640242382884026, -0.011506080627441406, -0.011862057261168957, 0.004521476104855537, 0.005150176584720612, -0.010357769206166267, -0.03421967849135399, 0.04545016586780548, -0.021232279017567635, 0.011356799863278866, 0.036929696798324585, -0.04680517315864563, -0.02436716854572296, 0.003970286808907986, -0.03483976796269417, -0.0002662647166289389, -0.03892775624990463, 0.0021545193158090115, 0.0016995009500533342, 0.024803526699543, -0.050158243626356125, 0.017075391486287117, -0.0065453751012682915, 0.01868302747607231, 0.0017497395165264606, 0.0031693396158516407, 0.006935800891369581, 0.029098210856318474]], "input": ["\"LEVEL OF DEMAND\":\"Demand is the quantity of a good or service which consumers want, and are willing and able to pay for. The level of demand influences pricing; the higher the demand, the higher the price that can be charged. Demand is influenced by factors such as income, price of substitute goods, price of complementary goods, consumer tastes and fashion, advertising, and consumer views and capacity to pay.\"", "\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND (PED)\":The price elasticity of demand (PED) is the degree of sensitivity of demand for a good to changes in the price of that good. It is calculated using the formula PED = % change in demand / % change in price. Generally, PED will be negative since a rise in price typically leads to a fall in demand, but the minus sign is conventionally ignored.", "\"ELASTIC DEMAND\":\"Elastic demand means that demand is very responsive to changes in price. The change in the quantity of goods demanded will be relatively greater (i.e., in percentage terms) than the change in price. The PED will be greater than one.\"", "\"INELASTIC DEMAND\":\"Inelastic demand means that a change in price will have little impact on demand. Demand will change by a relatively small amount (i.e., in percentage terms) than the change in price. The PED will be less than one.\"", "\"QUIZ: PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\":\"This quiz involves calculating the price elasticity of demand based on changes in price for a baker's doughnuts. It includes scenarios where the current price per doughnut is $4 and $2, requiring the calculation of elasticity and interpretation of results.\"", "\"COMPETITORS\":\"Competitors are other businesses offering similar products or services in the market. The presence of competitors can influence a company's pricing strategy and market power.\"", "\"CUSTOMERS\":\"Customers are the buyers of a company's products or services. The relationship with customers, including dominant customers and bulk buying, can affect pricing strategies.\"", "\"PERFECT COMPETITION\":Perfect competition is a theoretical market structure characterized by many sellers and buyers, identical or homogeneous products, and no barriers to entry. In this market, there is perfect information available to all participants, meaning that all buyers and sellers have full knowledge of prices and products. The sale and purchase of goods occur at the market clearing (or equilibrium) price, where supply and demand are equal, ensuring there is no excess or shortage. Market participants in perfect competition are 'price takers,' meaning they must accept the market price and cannot influence it.", "\"COST PLUS PRICING METHODS\":\"Cost plus pricing methods involve adding a given margin to the cost of a product. The cost may be the marginal cost, the full cost, or even the relevant cost.\"", "\"OPPORTUNITY COST PRICING\":\"Opportunity cost (relevant cost) pricing is suitable for short-term pricing decisions.\"", "\"MARGINAL COST\":\"Marginal cost\" refers to the cost of producing one additional unit of a product. It is equal to the variable cost per unit, at least until full capacity is reached. In the context of Division M, the marginal cost is $740.", "\"PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND\":Price elasticity of demand (PED) measures the responsiveness of the quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price. It is calculated as the percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price. If demand is price elastic, a decrease in price will lead to an increase in revenue. A value greater than 1 indicates elastic demand, meaning demand is sensitive to price changes. In essence, PED is a measure of the degree of sensitivity of demand for a good to changes in the price of that good.", "\"RISK\":\"Risk is the existence of several possible outcomes, which are known in advance along with the related probability.\"", "\"UNCERTAINTY\":\"Uncertainty refers to the potential outcomes of a decision that are not known in advance.\"", "\"EXPECTED VALUE\":\"Expected value (EV) = Weighted arithmetic mean of possible outcomes = \u03a3 (xi p(xi)). This formula represents the sum (\u03a3) of each possible outcome (Xi) multiplied by its probability of occurring (p(xi)).\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF EXPECTED VALUE\":\"When an unbiased six-sided die is thrown, each side has an equal chance (1/6) of being obtained. The expected value of throwing a dice many times is calculated as: EV = 21/6 or 3.5. This means that if the dice is thrown many times, the average value of the throws would be 3.5.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}